# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1818 Illinois lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on September 17, 1818, in order to elect the first lieutenant governor of Illinois upon Illinois acquiring statehood on December 3, 1818.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate Pierre Menard defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates William L.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, September 17, 1818, Democratic-Republican candidate Pierre Menard won the election by a margin of 1,219 votes against his foremost opponent and fellow Democratic-Republican candidate William L.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Reynolds, thereby gaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Menard was sworn in as the 1st lieutenant governor of Illinois on October 6, 1818.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The **1820 United States presidential election in Illinois** took place between November 1 and December 6, 1820, as part of the 1820 United States presidential election.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Voters chose three representatives, or electors, to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] It was the first presidential election that Illinois participated in since being admitted to the Union on December 3, 1818.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Illinois cast three electoral votes for the Democratic-Republican candidate and incumbent President James Monroe, as he ran effectively unopposed.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The electoral votes for vice president were cast for Monroe's running mate Daniel D.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The state was divided into electoral districts with one elector each, and each district's voters chose the electors.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-gubernatorial-election] The **1822 Illinois gubernatorial election** was Illinois's second gubernatorial election and its first competitive election.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-gubernatorial-election] All candidates in the election represented the Democratic-Republican Party except Edward Coles, who ran as an independent.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-gubernatorial-election] The election resulted in the narrow victory of anti-slavery Edward Coles over the pro-slavery Joseph Philips.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1822 Illinois lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on August 5, 1822, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Illinois.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate Adolphus Hubbard defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates James Lemen Jr. and John G.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1822-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Hubbard was sworn in as the 2nd lieutenant governor of Illinois on December 5, 1822.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The **1824 United States presidential election in Illinois** took place between October 26 and December 2, 1824, as part of the 1824 United States presidential election.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] During this election, the Democratic-Republican Party was the only major national party, and four different candidates from this party sought the Presidency.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Although Illinois voted for John Quincy Adams over Andrew Jackson, Henry Clay, and William H.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Crawford, the district-based system used for choosing electors meant that only one of the state's electoral votes were assigned to Adams, while the remaining two were assigned to Jackson.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] This was the first presidential election that four candidates each won at least one county in the same state.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] This feat would be shared by Virginia in the same election; however, the only other occurrences in presidential election history have been in 1860 (in Missouri), and in 1912 (in North Dakota and in Kansas).
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-gubernatorial-election] The **1826 Illinois gubernatorial election** was the third quadrennial election for this office.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-gubernatorial-election] Former Territorial Governor Ninian Edwards was elected with a 49% plurality.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-gubernatorial-election] State senator Thomas Sloo Jr. came in second and Former Lieutenant Governor Adolphus Hubbard came in third.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1826 Illinois lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on August 7, 1826, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Illinois.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate and incumbent member of the Illinois Senate William Kinney defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates Samuel S.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 7, 1826, Democratic-Republican candidate William Kinney won the election by a margin of 504 votes against his foremost opponent and fellow Democratic-Republican candidate Samuel S.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Thompson, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1826-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Kinney was sworn in as the 3rd lieutenant governor of Illinois on December 6, 1826.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] The **1864 Illinois gubernatorial election** was the thirteenth election for this office and took place during the American Civil War.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] Republican governor Richard Yates did not run for re-election, but was instead elected to serve in the United States Senate.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] Oglesby resigned his commission to run as the National Union nominee.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] Congressman James Carroll Robinson was the Democratic nominee.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] At this time in Illinois history, the Lieutenant Governor was elected on a separate ballot from the governor.
[src:1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election/1864-illinois-gubernatorial-election] This would remain the case until the adoption of the 1970 constitution.
